A band known as the Boys’ band was formed in 1936 with Sam Whitaker as conductor. Mr Whitaker passed away in 1940 and the band had various conductors until Ralph Skerritt took over and won D Grade in 1946. The band then changed its name to Excelsior and Boys and a lot of players resigned and joined the Federals. Mr A Connors took over the band in 1946 and over the years gradually became A Grade. The band lost a lot of players after the 1968 contest and amalgamated with the City and City Juniors in 1972.

This band was started by Mr. Zemek, who conducted the first civilian band in Maryborough, known as the Oddfellows, in the early years of the century. The band promoted the 1910/11 contest in Maryborough and in 1913/14 another contest where they won the B Grade competition. In 1914/15 Percy Code from Ballarat took the band and beat Ipswich Vice Regal for A Grade. The Vice Regals up until this time had been unbeaten. Mr. Ryder then took over the band and went to the 1918/19 contest where it won A Grade. Mr. Ryder resigned and Mr. Gus Cerezo took over guiding the band to second place in 1922. The band began to falter and Mr. Richard Zemek took over the band for a few years until 1926 when Mr. George Gummow took control and won the A Grade at Toowoomba and Mackay respectively in 1926 and 1927. In 1928 the band had reverted to B and C Grade and won the C Grade. Lou Gray followed Mr. Gummow and took the band to Sydney for an Australian Championship. Mr. Zemek took over the band again until a Mr. R P Moore assumed control in 1933. The band amalgamated with the Maryborough Federal in 1938.

This band was known as the Infant band beginning in 1917 when Mr. Sam Whitaker converted the Junior Naval band into a distinctive body naming it the Federals. The first win was in 1917/18 and again in 1927 when they lost by 1 point in C Grade. The band again lost by 1 point in C Grade in 1930. In 1933 Mr. Whitaker conducted 2 bands in Maryborough the Federal and Maryborough Town.

The band absorbed the Maryborough Naval band in 1938.

The Wide Bay Regiment Band began in the 1880's and was under the control of Mr. Alf Hall. In 1912 the Military band disbanded and the City Band was founded with Mr. Hall conducting for many years. The band struggled through the Great War and in 1921 at Bundaberg under Mr. W Ryder the band won the coveted Boosey Cup by 24 points. In 1927 the band went to contest under Mr. W H Partington and in 1930 the band competed in C Grade being conducted until 1948 by Jack Brennan. Jack normally stood down at contests to allow a coach to be appointed. By the 1960’s the numbers were depleted and a boys band was formed and was conducted by Fred Wedd, Don Perry and Erny Heitmann until the band amalgamated with the Excelsior and Boys in 1972.

Formed as Heap Bridge Brass Band in 1877 by members of Heap Bridge United Methodist Church, in 1881 became connected with the firm of Messrs. B. & G. Wrigley, woollen manufacturers. Began contesting that year and during the period to 1888 had won 14 prizes. A new set of instruments, value £400 and uniforms £120 were purchased in 1882. Known as 1st Volunteer Battalion Lancashire Fusiliers Band (later the Band of the Territorial Army 5th Battalion) between 1891 and 1918. After the war, they reverted to the title of Heap Bridge Brass Band. Became Bury Fire Brigade Band in 1939, and reformed in January 1946 as Bury Public Silver Band. Records of the band, from 1885-1914, are held at Bury Archive Service.

Not to be confused with an earlier [bands/bury-public|Bury Public] band.

Formed in November 1891 by Wm Norman Rayson. He had started earlier local bands at Breightmet Bleachworks, his place of work, and in the village of Ainsworth but both were short lived. In 1891 he again gathered together some local musicians and Ainsworth Brass Band was formed. In the mid 1890's the band was engaged to play at Bolton ice rink at the bottom of Chorley Old Road. The bandsmen would walk to Bolton and then at the end of the evening walk back at one or two o'clock in the morning, back to Ainsworth village. Often they would pause on their way home through the fields and enjoy an informal concert. Their best soloists would play and sing and the whole band would thoroughly enjoy themselves. On one November 5th the band found a deserted bonfire still burning. They gathered round and played 'Hail smiling Morn', the band serenaded the neighbourhood for a while before marching off to a lively quick march!
They changed their name to Ainsworth Public Subscription Band in 1946 after having been disbanded during the war. In the 1950's the band took sponsorship from a local firm and changed its name to the Irwell Forge Band. They were sponsored by Airtours the travel company in 1986. Following difficult trading conditions the sponsorship deal ended in 1989. Due to its Bury roots, and the fact that Bury Silver Band were not playing at that time, the band was renamed as Bury Brass Band. They played on under that name until 1997 when the band eventually folded due to lack of a fixed affordable rehearsal space and being down to twelve members. Conductors have included C. H. Partington (1933-38), Harry Hodgson (1938-48) and Frank Kay (c. 1950).

Was originally the band of the 24th Battalion Manchester Regiment which was raised as part of 'Kitcheners Army' in 1914/15.  Became Oldham Prize band after battalion was demobbed in 1919.

The famous Oldham Rifle Brigade band, after whom the march "O.R.B." was named (the composer, Charles Anderson, was the band's conductor), was founded in 1865 as a civilian band.

In 1871 it became affiliated to the local volunteer regiment, which underwent various name changes over the years, which are reflected (sometimes apparently inconsistently) in the names that the band contested under.

The history of the regiment name that the band was attached to is as follows:
February 1860 -  founded as 31st (Oldham) Lancashire Rifle Volunteers
November 1860 - became part of 7th Admin. Bn.
1880 - consolidated as 23rd corps, but changed back to 7th shortly thereafter
1882 - new corps formed with same personnel - 22nd Lancs. RVC
1888 - became 6th VB Manchester Regiment
1908 - became 10th Manchesters

The band was reformed after the 1914-18 war by Francis Miller, and continued as a brass band until 1934, when the War Office decreed that all military bands must become mixed brass/woodwind. It is not currently known how long the band continued after that date, although it is interesting that we have them recorded at Belle Vue in 1935.

Anne Stewart feedbacks:
"Just to inform you that my Grandfather was the F. Miller described as conductor at some of the contests. Francis Miller. He fought and was injured  at Gallipoli although came out of the band at that point to fight with his half brother who was not in the band. He ended up as Reg Sgt Major and bandmaster of the Manchester 10th and I believe that after the war he went to buy new silver for the regiment. I have photos of the band and Regiment and will try to find out if he conducted at any of the other contests. My father talked of going with my grandfather to the contest at Crystal Palace prior to the first World war. He says the band was mustered on the forecourt of Euston Fire Station in London and marched all the way to Crystal Palace. However my father did not remember them winning!"
"My Grandfather was Francis Miller mentioned above. I sent an earlier E mail. I think the H miller you have down as conducting the band in 1924 at Crystal Palace must in fact have been F Miller as my Father said they competed 3 times with him as bandmaster. My Uncle's Family account of his Father Francis Miller says After the 1918 war the band was reformed by my Grandfather and continued until 1934 when the war Office issued an order that all Army Bands had to be standerdised and turned into military bands. My Grandfather knew nothing of military bands with woodwind instruments and he struggled on for 2 years. He then left the army being too old and the 10th became a tank regiment."

We have two bands here. The original Burslem band, which Gavin believes folded in the 1st World War, and Burslem Co-op founded after the 2nd World War. Am currently reading The Bandsman's Everything Within (published 1950) states Burslem Co-op started life as Longton Town band in the 1920's., becoming Burslem Co-op in 1946. This would seem to be backed by the results above because between 1883 and 1903 the record is for 'Burslem' and then a gap of 43 years when the Co-op results commence. When we check the results for 'Longton' we have Longton, Longton Borough and Longton Rifles up to 1899. Longton Town then appear on 4 occassions between 1931 and 1937, have we an easy way to correct these results and place Longton Town and Burslem co-op together as well as seperate 'Burslem' from the Co-op ?

Believed formed 1840 at the factory of Jonas Brook and Brothers (Thread makers).  Factory closed in 1939 but the firm of David Brown Tractors took over the band.  The band was reformed after the Second World war as a public subscription band and adopted the the current name.

Update from Tony Clarke, Chairman and Trustee, 2020:

Our passed down information through families in the village is that Jonas Brook and Brothers took over the band in 1846 and founded it as a full Brass Band from an existing reed band.
When Jonas Brook and Brothers closed in 1939 the band was transferred to David Brown Tractors but ownership of the instruments and music was retained by the J. B. and B. family.
Towards the end of the war, due to shortage of players because of call up to the forces, the band activities were suspended.
Shortly after the war ended the band was reformed by two former players, Jack Manchester and John Redfearn who were tasked with training new players and presenting a concert in the village and if successful all instruments and music the possession of which had been retained by the Brook family, would be handed over in trust to the village and the band would then be known as Meltham and Meltham Mills Subscription Band, and run by trustees for the benefit of the villages of Meltham and Meltham Mills

Banding in Kidlington has a long history, with references in local newspapers going back to at least 1840. Kidlington Concert Brass was formed in 1992 from the merger of the century-old [bands/kidlington-silver|Kidlington Silver Band] with [bands/oxford-concert-brass|Oxford Concert Brass], who had originally formed in 1972 as an offshoot of existing Oxford bands,  primarily [bands/city-of-oxford-silver-band|City of Oxford], with some input from the famous [bands/morris-motors|Morris Motors] band. The merger between Kidlington Silver and Oxford Concert occurred when both bands found themselves short of players and in the lower reaches of the Championship section, OCB after many successful years there (including two London and Southern Counties area titles in the 1980s), KSB after a rapid rise through the sections under the leadership of [conductors/terry-brotherhood|Terry Brotherhood].

Following the merger, the band with its new name established an enviable reputation in the Championship section over the next two decades, mostly under the long leadership of [conductors/catherine-underwood|Catherine Underwood]. Following three years in the first section, with MD [conductors/d-wilson|Duncan Wilson] at the helm, the band has now returned to the Championship section.

1963: Founded as "Mid Hants Schools", by John Knight. 1973: Renamed as "Hampshire Youth Concert", at the suggestion of Decca, to coincide with a record release. During this era the band competed in a mix of youth and adult competitions, with some over-19 members remaining to play in the adult format events. As a distinction became clearer between these two entities, the distinction between the youth band and the youth training band became somewhat blurred, with substantial overlap in personnel. 1976: Formal separation of the county-supported under-19 band from the over-19 band, which was launched as Hampshire Concert Brass, now known as Otterbourne Brass. 1991: Renamed "Hampshire County Youth". I was 2nd trombone in John Knight's Mid Hants Youth Band in the mid '60s. One year we won the National Youth Brass Band Championship in St Pancras town hall, playing an Eric Ball March, the name of which escapes me.
